\c 1 
\ms Jonah runs away

\rem Childrens
\p \v 1 This message from [oeb:the \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah] came to Jonah, the son of Amittai: \v 2 “Arise, go to that great city, Nineveh, and preach against it; for their wickedness is known to me.” \v 3 But Jonah started to flee to Tarshish from the presence of [oeb:the \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah]. He went down to Joppa and found a ship going to Tarshish. So he paid the fare and went aboard to go with them to Tarshish from the presence of [oeb:the \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah].

\v 4 But [oeb:the \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah] made a furious wind blow over the sea, and there was such a great storm that the ship was in danger of breaking to pieces. \v 5 [oeb:The|:Then the] sailors were [oeb:terrified|:afraid] and each cried for help to his own god. They threw [oeb:the ship’s cargo|:] into the sea [oeb:|:the things that were in the ship, in order] to make [oeb:the ship|:it] lighter. \v 6 [oeb:Meanwhile|:But] Jonah had gone down into the bottom of the ship and lay fast asleep. \v 6 [oeb:The|:Then the] captain of the ship went and said to him, “How [oeb:can you sleep|:is it that you are asleep]? Call on your god; perhaps that god will think of us, so that we may not be lost.”
\p \v 7 [oeb:The sailors|:And they] said to one another, “Come, let us cast lots [oeb:to discover|:, that we may know] on whose account this evil has come upon us.” So they cast lots, and the lot [oeb:indicated|:fell upon] Jonah. \v 8 [oeb:So|:Then] they said to him, “Tell us, what is your business, and where do you come from? What is your country and to what [oeb:people|:race] do you belong?” \v 9 He [oeb:replied|:said to them], “I am a Hebrew, and a worshipper of [oeb:the \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah], the God of heaven, who made the sea and the dry land.” \v 10 Then the men were greatly frightened and said to him, “What [oeb:have you|:is this you have] done?” For they knew that he was fleeing from the presence of [oeb:the \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah], because he had told them.

\p \v 11 Then they said to him, “What [oeb:should|:shall] we do to you, [oeb:to make the sea|:that the sea may be] calm for us?” For the sea grew more and more stormy. \v 12 He said to them, “Take me up and throw me into the sea, and the sea will be calm for you, for I know that [oeb:it is because|:on account] of me this fierce storm has overtaken you.” \v 13 But [oeb:instead|:] the men rowed hard to get back to the land; they could not, however, for the sea grew more and more stormy ahead.
\p \v 14 [oeb:So|:Therefore] they cried to [oeb:the \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah] and said, “We [oeb:beg you|:beseech thee], [oeb:\nd Lord\nd*|:O Jehovah], we [oeb:beg you|:beseech thee], [oeb:don’t|:] let us [oeb:|:not] die for this man’s life, [oeb:and don’t|:nor] let us be guilty of shedding innocent blood, for [oeb:you are|:thou art] [oeb:the \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah]; [oeb:you have|:thou hast] done as it pleases [oeb:you|:thee].” \v 15 [oeb:And|:So] they took up Jonah, and threw him into the sea; and the sea became calm. \v 16 Then the men greatly feared [oeb:the \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah], and they offered a sacrifice and made vows to him.

\p [nrsv:\v 17|jps:\c 2 \v 1] But [oeb:the \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah] [oeb:arranged for|:prepared] a great fish to swallow Jonah, and Jonah was inside the fish three days and three nights. [oeb:|:There Jonah prayed to Jehovah his God; and Jehovah spoke to the fish, and it threw. Jonah out upon the dry land.]

