\c 3 
\ms The message to Nineveh

\rem Childrens
\p \v 1 This message from [oeb:the \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah] came to Jonah the second time, \v 2 “Arise, go to that great city, Nineveh, and proclaim to it the message that I tell you.” \v 3 So Jonah started for Nineveh, as [oeb:the \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah] commanded. Now Nineveh was so large a city that it took three days’ journey to cross it. [oeb:|:And]\v 4 Jonah began by going [oeb:a day’s journey into|:through] the city, [oeb:|:a day’s journey,] and he proclaimed, “Forty days more and Nineveh shall be overthrown.”
\p \v 5 And the people of Nineveh believed God; and they ordered a fast and put on sackcloth, from the greatest to the least of them. \v 6 And when word came to the king of Nineveh, he rose from his throne, took off his robe, dressed in sackcloth, and sat in ashes. \v 7 And he made this proclamation and published it in Nineveh: \v 8 “By the decree of the king and his nobles: [neut:People|masc:Man], beast, herd, and flock shall not taste anything; let them not eat nor drink water. \v 8 Let both [neut:people and animals|masc:man and beast] put on sackcloth and let them cry earnestly to God; let them each turn from [neut:their|masc:his] evil ways and from the deeds of violence which they are doing. \v 9 Who knows? God may relent and avert his fierce anger, [oeb:so|:] that we may not die.”
\p \v 10 When God saw that they turned from their evil course, he relented the evil which he said he would do to them, and did not do it.

\c 4 
\ms Jonah sulks

\p \v 1 But this [oeb:seemed very wrong to Jonah|:displeased Jonah very much] and he [oeb:became|:was] angry. \v 2 [oeb:He|:And he] prayed to [oeb:the \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah] and said, “Ah, [oeb:\nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah], wasn’t this what I said when I was still in my own country? That was why I fled at once to Tarshish; for I knew that [oeb:you are|:thou art] a gracious and merciful God, patient, and loving and ready to forgive. \v 3 Therefore, [oeb:\nd Lord\nd*|:O Jehovah], [oeb:|:take now,] I beg  [oeb:you|:thee], [oeb:take|:] my life from me; for it is better for me to die than to live!” \v 4 But [oeb:the \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah] said, “Are you doing right in being angry?”
\p \v 5 Then Jonah went out of the city and sat down on the east side, and there made a hut for himself and sat under it, [oeb:waiting to|:until he might] see what would become of the city. \v 6 And [oeb:the \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah] [oeb:arranged for|:prepared] a bush [oeb:to|:and made it] grow up over Jonah as a shade for his head [oeb:to make him comfortable|:]. [oeb:The|:So the] [oeb:bush|:gourd] gave Jonah great pleasure; \v 7 but at dawn the next day God [oeb:arranged for|:prepared] a worm which [oeb:attacked|:injured] the [oeb:bush|:gourd], so that it wilted. \v 8 And when the sun rose, God [oeb:arranged|:prepared] a hot east wind. And the sun beat upon Jonah’s head, so that he was faint and begged that he might die, saying, “It is better for me to die than to live.” \v 9 But God said to Jonah, “Are you doing right in being angry about the [oeb:bush|:gourd]?’ He replied, “[oeb:I have every right|:It is well for one] to be [oeb:as angry as I could possibly be|:angry, even to death]!”

\ms Jonah is rebuked

\p \v 10 [oeb:The \nd Lord\nd*|:Jehovah] said, “You care [oeb:about|:for] a [oeb:bush|:gourd] which has cost you no trouble and which you have not made grow, which came up in a night and wilted in a night. \v 11 Should I not care for the great city Nineveh, in which there are one hundred and twenty thousand people who do not know their right hand from their left; [oeb:and many|:besides much] cattle[oeb: too|:]?” 
